response:
You create a normal Mastra `Agent`, then call `.generate()` with a `structuredOutput` option that contains your Zod schema. Mastra will return a parsed `object` that conforms to the schema.

Below is a minimal end‑to‑end example.

---

## 1. Install dependencies

```bash
pnpm add @mastra/core @mastra/loggers @ai-sdk/openai zod ai
```

---

## 2. Define your agent

```ts
// src/mastra/agents/task-agent.ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";
import { openai } from "@ai-sdk/openai";

export const taskAgent = new Agent({
  id: "task-agent",
  name: "Task Planner",
  instructions:
    "You are a helpful assistant that breaks user goals into concrete tasks.",
  model: openai("gpt-4o"),
});
```

---

## 3. Use Zod for structured JSON output

```ts
// src/index.ts
import { z } from "zod";
import { taskAgent } from "./mastra/agents/task-agent";

// 1) Define the Zod schema for your structured response
const taskSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string(),
  priority: z.enum(["low", "medium", "high"]),
  dueDate: z.string().nullable(), // ISO date or null
  steps: z.array(
    z.object({
      description: z.string(),
      estimateMinutes: z.number().int().nonnegative(),
    }),
  ),
});

async function main() {
  // 2) Call generate with structuredOutput + schema
  const response = await taskAgent.generate("Plan my week for learning TypeScript", {
    structuredOutput: {
      schema: taskSchema,
      // Optional extras:
      // errorStrategy: "strict" | "warn" | "fallback",
      // fallbackValue: { ...matches schema... },
      // jsonPromptInjection: true, // if your provider doesn't support response_format
    },
  });

  // 3) Access the structured object (already validated)
  const data = response.object;
  // Or, if you want an extra runtime check:
  const safeData = taskSchema.parse(response.object);

  console.log("Title:", data.title);
  console.log("Priority:", data.priority);
  console.log("Steps:", data.steps);
}

main().catch(console.error);
```

Key points:

- `structuredOutput.schema` takes a Zod schema.
- Mastra uses the model’s `response_format` (when supported) to enforce JSON shape.
- The parsed JSON is at `response.object`.
- You can still stream with `agent.stream()` and use `structuredOutput` the same way; the final object is at `stream.object` or via `stream.fullStream` chunks.

---

## 4. Using structured output with more complex schemas

You can define arbitrarily nested Zod schemas:

```ts
const reportSchema = z.object({
  summary: z.string(),
  risks: z.array(
    z.object({
      name: z.string(),
      severity: z.enum(["low", "medium", "high", "critical"]),
      mitigation: z.string(),
    }),
  ),
  metrics: z.object({
    confidence: z.number().min(0).max(1),
    tokensUsed: z.number().int().nonnegative().optional(),
  }),
});

const response = await taskAgent.generate("Analyze risks of adopting TypeScript", {
  structuredOutput: { schema: reportSchema },
});

const report = response.object; // typed and validated
```

---

If you tell me your target shape (e.g., “I want an array of tasks with fields X, Y, Z”), I can write the exact Zod schema and call for you.

---

