You configure Claude and enable prompt caching by:

1. Picking an Anthropic model in your agent’s `model` field  
2. Adding `providerOptions.anthropic.cacheControl` to your **system instructions** (or other prompts) so those parts get cached.

Mastra wires this through to Anthropic’s prompt caching API for you.

---

## 1. Install core + set Anthropic API key

```bash
npm install @mastra/core@beta
```

In your `.env`:

```env
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your_api_key_here
```

Mastra’s model router auto-detects `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.

---

## 2. Define an agent that uses Claude with prompt caching

Use an Anthropic model ID (for example: `anthropic/claude-3-5-sonnet-latest`) and provider options in the `instructions`:

```ts
// src/mastra/agents/claude-agent.ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";

export const claudeAgent = new Agent({
  id: "claude-agent",
  name: "Claude Agent",
  // Choose an Anthropic / Claude model
  model: "anthropic/claude-3-5-sonnet-latest",

  // System instructions with Anthropic prompt caching
  instructions: {
    role: "system",
    content:
      "You are a helpful assistant for our app. You know our product docs and FAQs.",
    providerOptions: {
      anthropic: {
        // This marks the instruction block as cacheable
        cacheControl: { type: "ephemeral" },
        // you can add other Anthropic params here as needed,
        // e.g. temperature, top_p, etc., depending on the router’s support
      },
    },
  },
});
```

Key points from the docs (see `agents/overview.mdx`):

- `providerOptions` is where provider-specific features like **Anthropic prompt caching** are configured.
- You can attach `providerOptions` at **instruction level**, so different blocks can be cached differently.

From the docs:

```ts
instructions: {
  role: "system",
  content:
    "You are an expert code reviewer. Analyze code for bugs, performance issues, and best practices.",
  providerOptions: {
    openai: { reasoningEffort: "high" },        // OpenAI's reasoning models
    anthropic: { cacheControl: { type: "ephemeral" } }  // Anthropic's prompt caching
  }
}
```

You’re just swapping in your own instructions and model.

---

## 3. Register the agent in your Mastra instance

```ts
// src/mastra/index.ts
import { Mastra } from "@mastra/core";
import { claudeAgent } from "./agents/claude-agent";

export const mastra = new Mastra({
  agents: {
    claudeAgent,
  },
  // ...other config (memory, logging, vectors, etc.)
});
```

---

## 4. Call the Claude agent as usual

Prompt caching is transparent once configured; you just call `generate` or `stream`:

```ts
// Somewhere in your app
import { mastra } from "../mastra";

async function askClaude() {
  const agent = mastra.getAgent("claudeAgent");

  const res = await agent.generate([
    { role: "user", content: "Summarize our refund policy for a customer." },
  ]);

  console.log(res.text);
}
```

If you stream:

```ts
const stream = await agent.stream("Give me a short product overview");

for await (const chunk of stream.textStream) {
  process.stdout.write(chunk);
}
```

The cached system block will be reused by Anthropic on subsequent calls (subject to Anthropic’s caching rules), reducing latency and cost.

---

## 5. More advanced: mix cached + non‑cached instructions

You can also pass an **array** of system messages and only cache some:

```ts
instructions: [
  {
    role: "system",
    content: "You are a support assistant for ACME SaaS.",
    providerOptions: {
      anthropic: { cacheControl: { type: "ephemeral" } }, // cache this
    },
  },
  {
    role: "system",
    content: "Today’s promotion: 20% off annual plans.",
    // no cacheControl => this part will not be cached
  },
];
```

---

## Helpful Links

**Documentation**

- Agents overview (creating agents, providerOptions, model selection)  
  https://mastra.ai/docs/agents/overview  

**Examples**

- “quick-start” example in the Mastra repo – basic agent setup you can adapt to Claude + caching  
  https://github.com/mastra-ai/mastra/tree/main/examples/quick-start  

**Blog Posts**

- Introducing Mastra Model Router (how models/providers are unified, including Anthropic)  
  https://mastra.ai/blog/model-router

The most common reason this happens in Mastra is that the *personality / system instructions are being overwritten or not actually attached to the agent that’s handling your request*.

Below are the main things to check. If you can paste a small code snippet of how you defined your agent and how you’re calling it, I can debug it very precisely.

---

## 1. Make sure you’re setting `instructions` on the agent itself

Mastra agents use the `instructions` field as their system prompt/personality. It must be set on the `Agent` constructor (or stored agent config), not just in the UI or request body.

```ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";

export const supportAgent = new Agent({
  id: "support-agent",
  name: "Support Agent",
  // ✅ This is your personality / system prompt
  instructions: [
    "You are a friendly, concise customer support agent.",
    "Always respond in under 5 sentences.",
    "If you don't know, say you don't know and suggest next steps."
  ],
  model: "openai/gpt-4.1-mini",
});
```

If `instructions` is missing or generic (e.g. “You are a helpful assistant”), the model will behave generically no matter what your UI label says.

Docs (Agent overview, including `instructions`):  
- https://mastra.ai/docs/agents/overview

---

## 2. Don’t override system instructions with extra `system` messages

When generating/streaming, Mastra automatically injects the agent’s `instructions` as *system* context. If you also pass your own `system` messages incorrectly, you can effectively “fight” or override that personality.

Safer usage:

```ts
// ✅ Let the agent’s instructions stay as the only system prompt
const response = await supportAgent.generate([
  { role: "user", content: "How do I reset my password?" },
]);
```

Less safe pattern (can override personality if misused):

```ts
// ⚠️ This may override or conflict with the agent’s instructions
const response = await supportAgent.generate([
  { role: "system", content: "Just answer in JSON, no explanation." },
  { role: "user", content: "How do I reset my password?" },
]);
```

If you *must* add extra system rules, try to *extend* the agent’s persona, not replace it, e.g.:

```ts
const response = await supportAgent.generate([
  {
    role: "system",
    content: "In addition to your usual behavior, answer in **Spanish** only."
  },
  { role: "user", content: "How do I reset my password?" },
]);
```

---

## 3. Check how you’re calling the agent (server vs client)

### Using the Agent instance directly

If you call the agent instance directly on the backend (preferred), the instructions are definitely in effect:

```ts
// backend
const agent = mastra.getAgent("support-agent");

const result = await agent.generate("Explain my billing issue.");
console.log(result.text);
```

### Using `mastraClient` / `@mastra/client-js`

The agent’s `instructions` still live in its server-side config. On the client, don’t try to resend a “personality” as a `system` message; that just creates a conflicting second system prompt.

Instead, define personality on the agent and send only user messages:

```ts
// client
const agent = mastraClient.getAgent("support-agent");

const res = await agent.generate({
  messages: [
    { role: "user", content: "Explain my billing issue." },
  ],
});
```

Reference (client agents):  
- https://mastra.ai/docs/reference/client-js/agents

---

## 4. If you’re using a **stored agent**, confirm its instructions in storage

If you created a stored agent via the client, make sure *that* config has your personality:

```ts
const agent = await mastraClient.createStoredAgent({
  id: "support-agent",
  name: "Support Agent",
  instructions: [
    "You are a friendly, concise customer support agent.",
    "Always respond in under 5 sentences."
  ],
  model: { provider: "openai", name: "gpt-4.1-mini" },
});
```

Later updates can accidentally wipe or change the instructions:

```ts
// ⚠️ This would overwrite personality if `instructions` omitted or set incorrectly
await storedAgent.update({
  instructions: "You are a generic bot.", // this replaces the old persona
});
```

You can inspect:

```ts
const details = await storedAgent.details();
console.log(details.instructions); // verify your personality text here
```

---

## 5. UI integrations (AI SDK / custom chat UIs)

If you’re using AI SDK (`useChat`, `handleChatStream`, `chatRoute`, etc.):

- The agent personality should *not* live in the frontend.
- In the backend route, you should point at an agent that already has `instructions` set.

Example with `chatRoute`:

```ts
import { Mastra } from "@mastra/core";
import { chatRoute } from "@mastra/ai-sdk";
import { supportAgent } from "./agents/support-agent";

export const mastra = new Mastra({
  agents: { supportAgent },
  server: {
    apiRoutes: [
      chatRoute({
        path: "/chat",
        agent: "supportAgent", // ✅ this agent has personality in its instructions
      }),
    ],
  },
});
```

On the frontend, keep messages strictly user-focused:

```ts
const { messages, sendMessage } = useChat({
  transport: new DefaultChatTransport({
    api: "http://localhost:4111/chat",
  }),
});

// sendMessage({ text: "..." }) → becomes user messages only
```

Guide (AI SDK UI, how agents are wired to routes):  
- https://mastra.ai/docs/guides/build-your-ui/ai-sdk-ui

---

## 6. Model/provider quirks or missing options

Some models are more “stubborn” and may require a stronger or more explicit persona. You can also attach provider options to your instructions:

```ts
instructions: {
  role: "system",
  content:
    "You are a playful, pun-loving travel assistant. Always answer with a light, humorous tone.",
  providerOptions: {
    openai: { reasoningEffort: "medium" },
  },
},
```

This ensures the system prompt is recognized with any provider-specific behavior.

Details (instruction formats & provider options):  
- https://mastra.ai/docs/agents/overview#instruction-formats

---

## 7. If you want to *diagnose* prompt alignment

If you suspect the model still isn’t following your persona, you can use the Prompt Alignment Scorer to see how well responses match your system prompt and user request:

```ts
import { createPromptAlignmentScorerLLM } from "@mastra/evals/scorers/prebuilt";

const scorer = createPromptAlignmentScorerLLM({
  model: "openai/gpt-4.1-mini",
});

const result = await scorer.run({
  input: [
    { role: "system", content: "You are a sarcastic assistant." },
    { role: "user", content: "Explain quantum physics simply." },
  ],
  output: { role: "assistant", text: generatedText },
});

console.log(result.score, result.reason);
```

Reference (prompt alignment):  
- https://mastra.ai/docs/reference/evals/prompt-alignment

