You control both persona and temperature at the **Agent** level and/or per **request**.

Below are the two main pieces:

---

## 1. Persona = `instructions` on the Agent

Persona (tone, role, behavior) is set via the `instructions` field when you create your agent.

```ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";

export const supportAgent = new Agent({
  id: "support-agent",
  name: "Support Agent",
  instructions: [
    // High-level persona
    "You are a friendly, empathetic customer support chatbot.",
    // Style and constraints
    "Always respond in a concise, professional tone.",
    "If you don't know the answer, say so and suggest how the user might proceed.",
  ],
  model: "openai/gpt-5.1",
});
```

You can use:

- a single string
- an array of strings
- an array of `{ role: "system", content: string }` messages

as shown in the docs (from `agents/overview.mdx` and `reference/agents/agent.mdx`).

---

## 2. Temperature = model / options

Mastra uses model/router defaults, but you can control “creativity” (temperature-like behavior) in two common ways:

### A. Set defaults on the Agent (`defaultOptions`)

Use `defaultOptions` so every call shares the same settings:

```ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";

export const creativeChatbot = new Agent({
  id: "creative-chatbot",
  name: "Creative Chatbot",
  instructions: "You are a playful, imaginative writing assistant.",
  model: "openai/gpt-5.1",
  defaultOptions: {
    // AgentExecutionOptions – routed to the underlying model
    // For OpenAI-like models this includes temperature/topP/etc.
    // Example high-creativity:
    modelConfig: {
      temperature: 0.9,
      topP: 0.95,
    },
    maxSteps: 3,
  },
});
```

> The exact option shape is provider‑specific, but `defaultOptions` is where you attach those per‑agent defaults.

### B. Override per call (per message / per chat turn)

You can pass options when you call `generate` or `stream`:

```ts
// Very deterministic answer for this particular call
const response = await creativeChatbot.generate("Explain quantum computing simply", {
  modelConfig: {
    temperature: 0.1,
  },
});

console.log(response.text);
```

This lets you keep a general persona and default style on the agent, but tune creativity on individual turns (e.g., low temperature for factual answers, higher for brainstorming).

---

## 3. Putting it together – “chatbot” example

A typical chatbot agent:

```ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";

export const chatbot = new Agent({
  id: "main-chatbot",
  name: "Main Chatbot",
  instructions: [
    "You are a knowledgeable, friendly chatbot for our product.",
    "Always answer clearly and avoid jargon unless the user is technical.",
    "If the user asks for something you cannot do, explain the limitation politely.",
  ],
  model: "openai/gpt-5.1",
  defaultOptions: {
    modelConfig: {
      temperature: 0.4, // slightly creative but mostly stable
    },
  },
});

// Later in your app:
const reply = await chatbot.stream("Can you help me set this up?", {
  modelConfig: {
    temperature: 0.3, // optional: override per request
  },
});
```

