You can do this in Mastra in two main ways:

1. **Via the `Memory` options on an agent** (simplest; recommended)
2. **Via the `SemanticRecall` processor directly** (for full control)

Below is the recommended setup to have your agent *automatically* recall the 5 most relevant past messages on every call.

---

## 1. Install required packages

```bash
pnpm add @mastra/core @mastra/memory @mastra/libsql @ai-sdk/openai
```

This example uses LibSQL for storage/vector DB (the default in many Mastra examples).

---

## 2. Configure an agent with semantic recall (`topK = 5`)

```ts
// src/mastra/agents/memory-agent.ts
import { Agent } from '@mastra/core/agent';
import { Memory } from '@mastra/memory';
import { LibSQLStore, LibSQLVector } from '@mastra/libsql';
import { openai } from '@ai-sdk/openai';

// 1) Storage + vector for semantic recall
const storage = new LibSQLStore({
  id: 'agent-storage',
  url: 'file:./local.db', // or your LibSQL URL
});

const vector = new LibSQLVector({
  id: 'agent-vector',
  connectionUrl: 'file:./local.db',
});

// 2) Memory configured to pull 5 most relevant messages
const memory = new Memory({
  storage,
  vector,
  options: {
    // optional: how many most recent messages to always keep
    lastMessages: 10,

    // semantic recall: retrieve 5 most similar messages
    semanticRecall: {
      topK: 5,              // <= 5 most relevant messages
      messageRange: 0,      // no extra before/after; just the hits themselves
      scope: 'resource',    // search across all threads for this user
    },

    // optional, unrelated to topK but often useful
    workingMemory: { enabled: false },
  },
});

export const memoryAgent = new Agent({
  id: 'memory-agent',
  name: 'Memory Agent',
  instructions: 'You are a helpful AI agent with semantic memory.',
  model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
  memory,
});
```

### Why this gives you “5 most relevant messages”

- `semanticRecall.topK = 5` → semantic search returns **5 best-matching messages**.
- `messageRange: 0` → you only get those 5 messages, not extra before/after.
- Mastra injects these recalled messages into the prompt automatically on each call, as long as you pass `memory` (resource/thread) to the agent.

---

## 3. Wire the agent into your Mastra instance

```ts
// src/mastra/index.ts
import { Mastra } from '@mastra/core/mastra';
import { memoryAgent } from './agents/memory-agent';

export const mastra = new Mastra({
  agents: {
    memoryAgent,
  },
});
```

---

## 4. Use the agent with thread + resource IDs

You must provide both `resource` (user ID) and `thread` (conversation ID) so Mastra knows what to recall from.

```ts
// src/chat.ts
import { mastra } from './mastra';
import 'dotenv/config';

async function main() {
  const agent = mastra.getAgent('memoryAgent');

  const resource = 'user-123';        // stable user ID
  const thread = 'conversation-abc';  // this conversation/thread

  // First message: store something to recall later
  await agent.generate(
    'Remember that my favorite framework is Mastra.',
    {
      memory: {
        resource,
        thread,
      },
    },
  );

  // Later in the same thread, semantic recall will kick in:
  const res = await agent.generate(
    "What's my favorite framework?",
    {
      memory: {
        resource,
        thread,
      },
    },
  );

  console.log(res.text);
}

main().catch(console.error);
```

On the second call, Mastra:

1. Embeds the latest user message.
2. Semantically searches your stored messages (via `vector`).
3. Retrieves the **top 5** matching messages (`topK: 5`) and injects them into the prompt.

---

## 5. Alternative: using the `SemanticRecall` processor directly

If you need fully custom pipelines (e.g., combining recall with custom processors), you can instead wire the processor yourself:

```ts
import { Agent } from '@mastra/core/agent';
import { SemanticRecall, MessageHistory } from '@mastra/core/processors';
import { LibSQLStore, LibSQLVector } from '@mastra/libsql';
import { openai } from '@ai-sdk/openai';

const storage = new LibSQLStore({ id: 'store', url: 'file:./local.db' });
const vector = new LibSQLVector({ id: 'vec', connectionUrl: 'file:./local.db' });

const semanticRecall = new SemanticRecall({
  storage,
  vector,
  embedder: openai.embedding('text-embedding-3-small'),
  topK: 5,                 // 5 most relevant messages
  messageRange: 0,         // just those 5 messages
  scope: 'resource',
});

export const semanticAgent = new Agent({
  id: 'semantic-agent',
  name: 'Semantic Agent',
  model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
  inputProcessors: [
    semanticRecall,
    new MessageHistory({ storage, lastMessages: 10 }),
  ],
  outputProcessors: [
    semanticRecall,
    new MessageHistory({ storage }),
  ],
});
```

This is more advanced but gives you explicit control over when recall runs and how it interacts with other processors.

