You add long‑term memory in Mastra by attaching a `Memory` instance to your agent and using **threads + resource IDs** so conversations are stored and retrieved across sessions.

Below is a practical, step‑by‑step setup.

---

## 1. Install the memory package

```bash
pnpm add @mastra/core @mastra/memory @ai-sdk/openai ai
```

(Adjust if you already have some of these.)

---

## 2. Create a `Memory` instance

Mastra’s `Memory` manages:

- **Threads**: conversation timelines
- **Resources**: usually your user ID (so all that user’s threads are grouped)
- **Working memory**: what the model itself writes as “state”
- **Semantic recall** (optional): retrieve relevant past messages using vector search

Simple setup (in `mastra/agents/memory.ts` or inline):

```ts
import { Memory } from '@mastra/memory';

export const memory = new Memory({
  // You can start with defaults and tweak later
  options: {
    lastMessages: 10,        // how many recent messages to always send
    semanticRecall: true,    // enable vector-based recall of older history
    workingMemory: {
      enabled: true,
      template: `
<user_profile>
Name: (unknown)
Preferences: (none yet)
</user_profile>
      `,
    },
  },
});
```

This creates a memory backend (using Mastra Storage under the hood) that you can reuse across agents.

---

## 3. Attach memory to your agent

```ts
// mastra/agents/index.ts
import { openai } from '@ai-sdk/openai';
import { Agent } from '@mastra/core/agent';
import { memory } from './memory';

export const userAssistant = new Agent({
  id: 'user-assistant',
  name: 'User Assistant',
  instructions: `
You are a helpful assistant that remembers user details between sessions.

- Store important user facts (name, preferences, goals) in <working_memory> blocks.
- When the user returns, use working_memory + recalled history to personalize responses.
- Do not expose the raw working_memory; only use it to inform your replies.
`,
  model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
  memory,
});
```

Attach this agent to Mastra:

```ts
// mastra/index.ts
import { Mastra } from '@mastra/core/mastra';
import { userAssistant } from './agents';

export const mastra = new Mastra({
  agents: { userAssistant },
  logger: false,
});
```

---

## 4. Use `threadId` + `resourceId` in your chatbot backend

When you call the agent for a specific user, always pass:

- `resourceId`: the stable user ID (e.g., `user.id` from your auth system)
- `threadId`: the specific conversation session ID (you can reuse it across days if you want a “single long‑running chat”)

Example minimal chat loop (Node):

```ts
import { randomUUID } from 'crypto';
import { mastra } from './mastra';

const agent = mastra.getAgent('userAssistant');

async function chatWithUser(userId: string, threadId?: string) {
  const resourceId = userId;
  const activeThreadId = threadId ?? randomUUID();

  const res = await agent.stream('Hi, I am back!', {
    resourceId,
    threadId: activeThreadId,
  });

  // Handle streaming text (simplified)
  for await (const chunk of res.textStream) {
    process.stdout.write(chunk);
  }

  return activeThreadId;
}
```

As long as you keep using the same `resourceId` and `threadId` for that user, Mastra will:

- Store each turn of the conversation
- Use recent history + semantic recall + working memory to bring relevant info back into context next time

---

## 5. Teach the model to save “long‑term” details

The model only remembers what it **writes into working memory** (because you’ll likely truncate full history to keep prompts small).

You do this by adding instructions like:

```ts
instructions: `
You are a helpful assistant.

Any time the user tells you:
- their name
- long‑term preferences (e.g., favorite topics, languages, formats)
- ongoing projects or goals

you MUST save or update them in a <working_memory> block at the end of your reply.

Example:

<working_memory>
name: Alice
language_preference: English
favorite_topics: startups, design
</working_memory>
`
```

Mastra’s `Memory` will detect `<working_memory>...</working_memory>` and store it, and will inject it back into future prompts.

---

## 6. Example: full memory‑enabled todo agent (from the example)

This pattern is already implemented in the `memory-todo-agent` example. Key bits:

```ts
// mastra/agents/index.ts
import { openai } from '@ai-sdk/openai';
import { Agent } from '@mastra/core/agent';
import { Memory } from '@mastra/memory';

const memory = new Memory({
  options: {
    lastMessages: 1,
    semanticRecall: false,
    workingMemory: {
      enabled: true,
      template: `
# Todo List
## Active Items
- Example (Due: Feb 7 3028, Started: Feb 7 2025)
  - Description: This is an example task - replace with whatever the user needs

## Completed Items
- None yet
`,
    },
  },
});

export const todoAgent = new Agent({
  id: 'todo-agent',
  name: 'TODO Agent',
  instructions: `
You are a helpful todolist AI agent...
You MUST save the todolist in every response message by printing out <working_memory> blocks.
If you do not save it in working_memory you will forget...
`,
  model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
  memory,
});
```

And usage (simplified):

```ts
const agent = mastra.getAgent('todoAgent');
const resourceId = 'SOME_USER_ID';
const threadId = 'SOME_PERSISTENT_THREAD_ID';

await agent.stream('Add buy milk tomorrow at 5pm.', {
  resourceId,
  threadId,
});
```

Open the same `resourceId` + `threadId` tomorrow, and the todo list is still there.

---

## 7. Privacy & data model tips

- Use **user IDs**, not emails, as `resourceId` (easy to rotate/anonymize).
- Let users reset memory: call `memory.deleteMessages` or start a fresh thread.
- For multi‑device: store `threadId` in your DB per “conversation” or “chat room” and reuse it across devices.

