Your bot is resetting because Mastra’s memory isn’t actually being used on each request. There are three things you must have working together:

1. Memory enabled on the agent  
2. A storage provider configured  
3. `memory: { resource, thread }` passed on every `generate` / `stream` call

If any of these are missing, the conversation will appear stateless.

Below is a checklist plus minimal code to compare with your setup.

---

## 1. Enable memory on the agent

Make sure your agent is created with a `Memory` instance:

```ts
// src/mastra/agents/chat-agent.ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";
import { Memory } from "@mastra/memory";

export const chatAgent = new Agent({
  id: "chat-agent",
  name: "Chat Agent",
  model: "openai/gpt-4.1-mini",
  instructions: "You are a helpful assistant.",
  memory: new Memory({
    options: {
      lastMessages: 20, // how many recent messages to include as context
    },
  }),
});
```

If `memory` is not set here, nothing will be stored.

Docs source: `agents/agent-memory.mdx`, `memory/overview.mdx`, `reference/memory/memory-class.mdx`.

---

## 2. Configure storage (so memory actually persists)

Memory needs a storage provider. Either:

### Global storage on the Mastra instance

```ts
// src/mastra/index.ts
import { Mastra } from "@mastra/core";
import { LibSQLStore } from "@mastra/libsql";

export const mastra = new Mastra({
  // ...
  storage: new LibSQLStore({
    id: "mastra-storage",
    url: "file:./mastra-storage.db", // NOT ":memory:" for persistence
  }),
});
```

Using `":memory:"` keeps data only in-process (lost on restart). For a real bot, use a file or external DB.

or

### Dedicated storage per agent

```ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";
import { Memory } from "@mastra/memory";
import { LibSQLStore } from "@mastra/libsql";

export const chatAgent = new Agent({
  id: "chat-agent",
  name: "Chat Agent",
  memory: new Memory({
    storage: new LibSQLStore({
      id: "chat-agent-storage",
      url: "file:./chat-agent-memory.db",
    }),
    options: {
      lastMessages: 20,
    },
  }),
});
```

If no storage is configured anywhere, the agent can’t persist history.

Docs source: `memory/overview.mdx`, `agents/agent-memory.mdx`.

---

## 3. Always send `resource` and `thread` with each call

Even with memory configured, Mastra will not save history unless both are provided.

```ts
// Example: in your route / handler
const response = await chatAgent.generate(userMessage, {
  memory: {
    resource: userId,          // stable user identifier
    thread: conversationId,    // ID for this chat thread
  },
});
```

From `memory/threads-and-resources.mdx`:

> “Even with memory configured, agents won’t store or recall information unless both `thread` and `resource` are provided.”

Common pitfalls that cause “resets every time”:

- Using a new/random `thread` for every request (e.g., `thread: crypto.randomUUID()` each time)  
- Omitting `resource` or `thread`  
- Changing `resource` between messages  
- Not wiring these through from your UI (e.g., React / Next.js / AI SDK hook)

If your UI uses something like `threadId` from a chat component, you should map it to Mastra:

```ts
await chatAgent.stream(input, {
  memory: {
    resource: session.user.id,    // or cookie / auth ID
    thread: uiThreadId,           // chat UI’s thread id
  },
});
```

