You add document search by wiring Mastra’s RAG system into your agent as a **tool** that queries your vector store.

Here’s the minimal end‑to‑end shape:

1. **Ingest your documents into a vector DB**
2. **Create a vector query tool (`createVectorQueryTool`)**
3. **Attach that tool to your agent**
4. (Optional) Add the vector‑store prompt string to instructions for better filtering

Below is a concrete example using Postgres + pgvector, but the pattern is the same for MongoDB, Pinecone, etc.

---

## 1. Install packages

```bash
npm install @mastra/core@beta @mastra/rag @mastra/pg ai zod
```

Make sure you have:

```bash
OPENAI_API_KEY=...
POSTGRES_CONNECTION_STRING=...
```

---

## 2. Ingest & index your documents

Run this once (or in a background job) to chunk, embed, and store documents.

```ts
// src/mastra/rag/index-docs.ts
import { embedMany } from "ai";
import { ModelRouterEmbeddingModel } from "@mastra/core/llm";
import { PgVector } from "@mastra/pg";
import { MDocument } from "@mastra/rag";

const MODEL_ID = "openai/text-embedding-3-small";
const INDEX_NAME = "docs_embeddings"; // must follow pgvector naming rules

export async function indexDocuments() {
  // 1. Load your raw docs (replace with your own loader)
  const docsText = [
    { id: "doc-1", text: "First document contents here..." },
    { id: "doc-2", text: "Second document contents here..." },
  ];

  // 2. Convert to MDocument & chunk
  const allChunks: { text: string; docId: string }[] = [];

  for (const doc of docsText) {
    const mdoc = MDocument.fromText(doc.text, { docId: doc.id });

    const chunks = await mdoc.chunk({
      strategy: "recursive",
      maxSize: 512,
      overlap: 50,
    });

    for (const chunk of chunks) {
      allChunks.push({
        text: chunk.text,
        docId: doc.id,
      });
    }
  }

  // 3. Embed all chunks
  const { embeddings } = await embedMany({
    values: allChunks.map((c) => c.text),
    model: new ModelRouterEmbeddingModel(MODEL_ID),
  });

  // 4. Store in pgvector
  const store = new PgVector({
    id: "pg-vector",
    connectionString: process.env.POSTGRES_CONNECTION_STRING!,
  });

  // Create index once (dimension must match the embedding model)
  await store.createIndex({
    indexName: INDEX_NAME,
    dimension: embeddings[0].length,
  });

  await store.upsert({
    indexName: INDEX_NAME,
    vectors: embeddings,
    metadata: allChunks.map((chunk) => ({
      text: chunk.text,
      docId: chunk.docId,
    })),
  });

  console.log("Documents indexed into", INDEX_NAME);
}

// If you want to run as a script:
// indexDocuments().catch(console.error);
```

After this, your docs are searchable via vector similarity.

---

## 3. Create a vector query tool for the agent

```ts
// src/mastra/tools/vector-query.ts
import { createVectorQueryTool } from "@mastra/rag";
import { ModelRouterEmbeddingModel } from "@mastra/core/llm";

export const searchDocsTool = createVectorQueryTool({
  vectorStoreName: "postgres",     // pgvector via @mastra/pg
  indexName: "docs_embeddings",
  model: new ModelRouterEmbeddingModel("openai/text-embedding-3-small"),
  databaseConfig: {
    pgvector: {
      minScore: 0.7, // filter out weak matches
    },
  },
});
```

---

## 4. Attach the tool to your agent

```ts
// src/mastra/agents/doc-agent.ts
import { Agent } from "@mastra/core/agent";
import { PGVECTOR_PROMPT } from "@mastra/pg";
import { searchDocsTool } from "../tools/vector-query";

export const docAgent = new Agent({
  id: "doc-agent",
  name: "Documentation Search Agent",
  model: "openai/gpt-5.1",
  instructions: `
You are a documentation assistant. 
Use the SearchDocs tool to look up relevant information in the knowledge base
BEFORE answering questions.
If you cannot find relevant info, say so clearly.

${PGVECTOR_PROMPT}  // helps the model form valid filters when needed
`,
  tools: {
    searchDocs: searchDocsTool,
  },
});
```

---

## 5. Register and call the agent

```ts
// src/mastra/index.ts
import { Mastra } from "@mastra/core";
import { docAgent } from "./agents/doc-agent";

export const mastra = new Mastra({
  agents: { docAgent },
  // add vector store registration here if needed for your setup
});
```

Usage:

```ts
// e.g. in an API route or script
import { mastra } from "./mastra";

async function askAgent(question: string) {
  const agent = mastra.getAgent("docAgent");

  const response = await agent.generate([
    { role: "user", content: question },
  ], {
    maxSteps: 4, // lets it call the search tool multiple times if needed
  });

  console.log(response.text);
}

askAgent("What does the first document say about X?");
```

This gives your agent a **tool‑driven document search** capability: it embeds the user’s query, searches your vector DB, gets the most relevant chunks, and then answers grounded in that context.

